As one said, “Though I am great sinner, Christ is a greater savior.” With that said, what may come, cancer or not, I will glorify God through the trials, the suffering because I know it will give way to something far more greater…(19)

A sweet friend said to me that the Lord is placing me through the refining fires and my late Pastor Doug Heck once said when my dad and brother died that the Lord has something special planned for me. (18)

My wife has been here with me and supporting me as well as you all and my church. The love shown amazes me. Whatever the diagnosis? Whatever is to come? I find myself clutching onto Christ in this time of trial. (17)

I am ready to drink from this cup that He given me. I am scared, but I am relying on His promises, I am clinging so tightly to Cross, clutching onto the hem of His robe. There is nothing else. It is Christ alone. (16)

We are appointed our time here and then we like flowers for s season, die. Psalm 103, which I am been meditating on everyday reminds me that He knows my frame and that I am dust, but He is so merciful and forgiving. Even to me, a wretch of a man. (15)
I must admit, I have wasted so much of my time in sin in the past. I have been lazy minded and a procrastinator, a battle I still fight daily. (14)

At the same time, I have been praying about death and asking the Lord to prepare me for that inevitable day. If my kidney should need be removed, I’ll have a 5 year lifespan or so the science says. (13)
I know not the outcome of this or what will happen. I’m thankful that the mass is small and slow growing. That is the kindness of the Lord. (12)
I have often been stuck too much in this world, materialistic and horizontally minded; not heavenly minded. I am guilty of that sin and have been for so long. (11)

Am I nervous of course, but there is a peace that I can not explain presently within me. I’ve been thinking of Paul and his comment in Phill, where is says “To live is Christ and to die is gain (to have more Christ). I’ve been thinking about that. (10)

I have been given great encouragement for fellow friends who are doctors and such love from you all and my church. This also has taught me that I truly have no control over my life. It is God that holds me in His hands and this trial is the cup that He has given to me. (9)

I am thankful for His mercy in doing so. Getting this mass caught early is a good sign. However, I must wait till Jan 20 for an appointment with the urologist to see if this mass is cancerous or just a cyst. It can certainly make a man like me, lacking patience crazy (8)

Now, a new trial has been placed upon me. A cyst or mass that is 1 CM has been located on my left kidney. All this was found incidentally by a simple CT, but it really was the Providence of God that brought it to the attention of the doctors. (7)
I don’t have a date of my salvation. I don’t have an experience. It was through stages I suppose. He was pruning me of the dross. Of which I am thankful. (6)
I prayed fervently through the flood of tears. I sought Jesus in the darkest pit that I was in. He in His mercy pulled me up from the pit of destruction that I was in. (5)

Yet, God was working in me. He stripped me of myself. My self dependence. My self will. He rattled me awake from the slumber that I was in to be honest. The fear of being separated from God scared me. (4)

I would have nightmares of being separated from God. Doubts would overcome me like a rogue wave. I was in the pit. I stayed a week in the VA Mental Health facility due to suicidal thoughts, a breakdown, and the pain of loss. (3)

Their deaths caused me to spiral downward with massive anxiety attacks and panic attacks. They were the last of my family. At the same time, the event caused me to stop and examine myself, my soul in relation to God.(2)

He alone will give you rest.
Bear each others burdens. Hug each other and cry upon each other’s shoulders tomorrow. Gather together and bring all of it to the Lord and know He is calling out to you and waving you to his embrace.

So, as you sleep this night, you might be thinking of your loved one. You might spend the night in tears like I have. Go ahead to do so, but take those tears and take them to the Lord. He is a gracious and compassionate Savior who willing and wanting to forgive sins.

So, to you out there who have lost loved ones like I have. You’re not alone. It’s okay to cry and grieve, it’s okay to go to church and cry. It’s okay. Let the tears flow and know that the Lord, the Great Shepherd is there with you, with me, with His flock.
When you find yourself not wanting to pray or read, read and pray, even if it is short. I need to be reminded of His promises, promises that He, the Lord of All, will never break.

I can sit here and vent about the broken and evil system that failed my father and brother, but that would be a waste of time. Instead, that time I should spend in prayer, seeking the healing touch of the Lord. His Words are such words of tender care.

I heard a quote by Samuel Rutherford the other day, “When I am in the cellar of affliction, I look for the Lord's choicest wines.” For me, the choicest of wines have been the Psalms and portions of the Gospel where Jesus says, “Come to me”
Yes, we will continue to weep here for our loved ones. I surely will shed tears daily for my father, brother, and mother whom I can only see in my minds eye now and through pictures.
The day shall come when all our tears will be permanently wiped away. Death will be no more. Our anxiety, our fears, our sorrows, our depressions, panic attacks, broken hearts will be no more.

That’s why we gather. We are imperfect. We are broken. We are filled with sorrow. It is okay to sit in the pew and cry before the Cross. It is okay because Jesus bends down and with His finger gently wiped away these tears.

This is why the church is remedy, the balm for us who are in such pain. We can come together as a body and share our burdens and serve one another during this time. It is okay to come to church and shed tears, it’s okay.
As for my father and brother, I know that I am not alone. There are many of you on here who have lost a family member or members. You are not alone in your grief, sorrow, and anguish.
It was a wake up call. One that I needed.

We can be often deceived of our salvation and sometimes, the Lord sends us a reality check to remind us of the brevity of this life. The unexpected deaths of my father and brother woke me up to the reality that I was not taking Him seriously.

I often pray why? Why him? Why did you spare me Lord of this Covid? Yet, the Lord needs not tell me. This season, this year has been about patience with me and waiting on the Lord. It has been a season of having my heart checked and examined.

It was never to be though. You can feel your siblings fear, even thousands of miles apart. Grant it, we didn’t have close conversations, I could feel his fear as he lie alone in that cold room surrounded by masked strangers.

Our last conversation on the phone as I recall, was that I told him I loved him and my stepmom would convey through those FaceTime messages that I loved him and that I was going to come up there and tend to him when he got out.

He didn’t think that he was going to die there alone. He was surrounded by strangers. The only connection to family was through FaceTime with my Stepmom. He was sedated and intubated. In a way, I am thankful that I did not see him like that.

As I sat in bed tonight, my eyes closed, my right hand pretended that I was caressing my little brother’s forehead and holding his hand in that hospital room he was in. I transport myself there in my dreams, thoughts, wishing I was there with him. He went in alone.
